9 ²¹ AEned] Antenor, who was the particular friend of AEneas, entertained Menelaus and Ulysses, when they went as ambassa— dors (see 11. 3. 201.) to Troy to demand Helen and her pro- perty. As a great proof how sacred the laws of hospitality in those days were held, we find Diomedes and Glaucus, when about to engage in mortal combat, parting as devoted friends, on finding that their fathers were pledged to each other by the ties of hospi- tality.
